05656nam a22008055i 9781400820818DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19921993nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008208187 a10.1515/97814008208182doi  a(DE-B1597)446046  a(OCoLC)979685145  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBJ1012 .P76 1993 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a170.4400aProspects for a Common Morality /ced. by Gene Outka, John P. Reeder.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[1992] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter 1. COMMON MORALITY AND THE COMMUNITY OF RIGHTS -- tChapter 2. COMMON MORALITY AND KANT’S ENLIGHTENMENT PROJECT -- tChapter 3. THE NATURE AND BASIS OF HUMAN RIGHTS -- tChapter 4. RELIGIOUS ETHICS IN A PLURALISTIC SOCIETY -- tChapter 5. AUGUSTINIANISM AND COMMON MORALITY -- tChapter 6. CLAIMS, RIGHTS, RESPONSIBILITIES -- tChapter 7. FEMINISM AND UNIVERSAL MORALITY -- tChapter 8. FOUNDATIONS WITHOUT FOUNDATIONALISM -- tChapter 9. ON HAVING A MORALITY IN COMMON -- tChapter 10. CONFLICTS AMONG IDEALS OF HUMAN FLOURISHING -- tChapter 11. THE PRIORITY OF DEMOCRACY TO PHILOSOPHY -- tChapter 12. TRUTH AND FREEDOM: A REPLY TO THOMAS MCCARTHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume centers on debates about how far moral judgments bind across traditions and epochs. Nowadays such debates appear especially volatile, both in popular culture and intellectual discourse: although there is increasing agreement that the moral and political criteria invoked in human rights documents possess cross-cultural force, many modern and postmodern developments erode confidence in moral appeals that go beyond a local consensus or apply outside a particular community. Often the point of departure for discussion is the Enlightenment paradigm of a common morality, in which it is assumed that certain unchanging beliefs inhere in the structure of human reason. Whereas some thinkers continue to defend this paradigm, others modify it in diverse ways without abandoning entirely the attempt to address a universal audience, and still others jettison virtually all of its distinguishing features. Exhibiting a range of positions Western participants take in these debates, this volume seeks to advance the substance of the debates themselves without prejudging the outcome. Rival assessments of the Enlightenment paradigm are offered from various philosophical and theological points of view. In addition to the editors, the contributors include Robert Merrihew Adams, Annette C. Baier, Alan Donagan, Margaret A. Farley, Alan Gewirth, David Little, Richard Rorty, Jeffrey Stout, and Lee H. Yearley.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEthics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Robert Merrihew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaier, Annette C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonagan, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarley, Margaret A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGewirth, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittle, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOutka, Gene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOutka, Gene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReeder Jr., John P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReeder, John P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel